<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>A decrease in business taxes would most directly affect which component of aggregate demand?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Consumption</option>
            <option letter="b">Investment</option>
            <option letter="c">Government spending</option>
            <option letter="d">Net exports</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Lower business taxes increase the expected return on investment projects, directly affecting investment spending as firms have more after-tax income for capital expenditures.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to equilibrium price and output when both AD and SRAS increase?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Price increases, output increases</option>
            <option letter="b">Price increases, output decreases</option>
            <option letter="c">Price effect is ambiguous, output increases</option>
            <option letter="d">Price decreases, output increases</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>When both AD and SRAS increase, output definitely increases, but the price effect depends on the relative magnitude of the shifts in AD and SRAS.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Cost-push inflation can result from which of the following?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">An increase in consumer spending</option>
            <option letter="b">An increase in government spending</option>
            <option letter="c">A decrease in raw material prices</option>
            <option letter="d">An increase in oil prices</option>
        </options>
        <answer>d</answer>
        <explanation>Cost-push inflation occurs when production costs rise, such as through higher oil prices, causing the SRAS curve to shift left and pushing up the price level.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>When the economy is operating below potential GDP, which gap exists?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Inflationary gap</option>
            <option letter="b">Recessionary gap</option>
            <option letter="c">Production gap</option>
            <option letter="d">Supply gap</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>A recessionary gap exists when actual real GDP is less than potential GDP, indicating the economy is operating below its full-employment level.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
